citations.narrative:
Multiple sharp penetrating screws are present on the interior surface of a wooden den box for 2 adult ring-tailed lemurs
that are outdoor housed on an island located near the flume ride. Surfaces in nonhuman primate enclosures that have
sharp or jagged edges may cause bodily harm to the animals. Any surfaces that come in contact with nonhuman primates
must be free of jagged edges or sharp points that might injure the animals.
Correct by 07 February 2025.

In an enclosure with 41 axis deer, the outer wall of the barn has been worn away by animal activity with several large
holes. The front section of the wall has become irregular and sharp, which may pose an injury risk to animals. Facilities
must be structurally sound, constructed with material that is an appropriate strength for the animals involved and shall be
maintained in good repair.
Correct by 21 February 2025.

Several issues were noted around the perimeter fence. These include a large, approximately 18-inch diameter hole, was
in the upper section of the western edge of the perimeter fence. A large tree had an approximately 1-foot diameter limb
that was broken and extended out of the perimeter fence to the ground. In a back area there were several fence panels
leaning against the inside of the perimeter. There were additional areas where old cages were piled directly against the
perimeter fence that could be used by escaped animals to more easily breach the perimeter fence. At the front section of
the facility, palm trees have grown flat and then extend up and are in-contact with the top of the fence. The primary
enclosure housing 6 bar-headed geese is 19 inches away from the perimeter fence. The fence must be constructed so
that it protects the animals in the facility by restricting animals and unauthorized persons from going through or under it
and having contact with the animals of the facility and so that it can function as a secondary containment system for the
animals in the facility. Additionally, the distance between primary enclosures and the perimeter fence must be at least 3
feet unless approved in writing by the Administrator.
Correct by 28 March 2025.

During the second day of the inspection on 15 January 2025, the outdoor primary enclosure for one adult sarus crane was
covered in standing water. A facility representative stated a water hose was accidentally left on overnight in the enclosure.
The bird was observed to walk through and stand in standing water in order to access shelter, food or drinking water.
Animals that do not have access to sufficient dry areas or must wade through water to access resources may experience
discomfort or distress. A suitable method shall be provided to rapidly eliminate excess water. The method of drainage
shall comply with applicable Federal, State, and local laws and regulations relating to pollution control or the protection of
the environment.
Correct from this date forward of 24 January 2025.

At time of inspection, there were multiple avian enclosures with defects in the mesh netting. In an enclosure housing two
adult Eurasian eagle owls, there were two openings in the north facing netting that measure approximately 4 inches in
diameter. Additionally, there were fist-sized holes in the overhead netting of the walk-through aviary housing two adult
white-faced whistling-duck, one adult cape thick-knee, four adult hadada ibis, five adult Abdim's stork, and seven adult
bald ibis. An approximately 5-inch diameter opening was observed in the netting of a single adult stanley crane's
enclosure adjacent to the walk-through aviary. Enclosures in need of repairs such as these cannot reliably contain the
birds inside or prevent the entry of birds and other animals from the outside. Birds could escape or become injured or ill
due to entry of outside birds or other animals. A worker was called to make repairs to the open tears within reach when
the inspector called attention to them during the inspection.
The facility must ensure that primary enclosures are designed and constructed of suitable materials so that they are
structurally sound and kept in good repair to protect the health of the birds and to contain the birds while restricting the
entry of outside animals.
Correct by 31 January 2025.

Multiple instances of exposed/protruding sharp points were observed within several avian enclosures that could lead to
potential injury of the birds housed within:
1- The emu enclosure had an approximately 2 feet long section of chain link of the top that had come apart with many
exposed wire points.
2- An enclosure with two stanley cranes had 3 sections of 1 inch-by-1 inch wire which were split with exposed wire points.
There was also a 1-inch strip of metal support strap with exposed screws.
3- There was a section on the top of chain link fence in the cassowary enclosure that had come apart with exposed sharp
points.
4- The sharp edges of corrugated metal roofing used on 4ft tall wooden structures in an enclosure with a sarus crane, a
second enclosure containing two marabou storks, a third enclosure housing approximately 27 birds representing mixed
waterfowl species (referred to as the geriatric pen), and a fourth enclosure containing a ruddy shelduck and a southern
screamer.
Primary enclosures must be constructed and maintained so that they have no sharp points or edges that could injure the
birds.
Correct by 07 February 2025.

citations.desc: Environment enhancement to promote psychological well-being.
citations.narrative:
There is no developed and documented plan for additional environment enhancement for nestlings, chicks or fledglings.
At time of inspection, a single juvenile finch is being parent raised in a designated room with hutches, but there is not a
written plan for this additional environment enhancement. Failure to develop and document a plan for special
consideration birds may result in inadequate or intermittent care in promoting and addressing needs for nestlings, chicks
or fledglings. Certain birds must be provided special attention regarding enhancement of their environment in accordance
with the instructions of the attending veterinarian.
Correct by 07 February 2025.

Two adult blue and gold macaws placed on a high perch at the front entrance during exhibition hours have a single metal
bowl-shaped water receptacle that has exterior rusting and is dripping water. The inspectors were unable to see the
interior of the water receptacle and the facility representative stated that there is no insert or liner to the bowl. Rusty water
receptacles cannot be properly cleaned and sanitized and their use for birds may result in the animals’ injury or poor
health. Water receptacles must be kept clean and sanitized in accordance with subsection 3.158 as often as necessary to
keep them free of contamination.
Correct by 31 January 2025.
This inspection and exit interview were conducted with the facility representatives.
Additional Inspectors:
Geoffrey Olsen, VETERINARY MEDICAL OFFICER n
